Ceratophrys ensenadensis
is based on three specimens from Olivos ( Fig. 1 , locality 10), province of Buenos Aires , Argentina . In this area, as in other regions of the Rio de la Plata, a series of deposits attributed to the Ensenada Formation, known as “toscas del Río de la Plata”, were exposed and provided many fossils (
Soibelzon et al. 2008
). Given the growth of the city of Buenos Aires , and the reclamation of land along the river, these deposits are now confined to small areas. The “toscas of Rio de la Plata” are thought to have been deposited during the early and middle Pleistocene (
Soibelzon et al. 2008
).
